<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-191-864  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 191 864.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Feb 19 1990 v11 n8 p4(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Gateway directly links SQL Server to DB/2. (Microsoft Corp andMicro Decisionware Inc introduce Database Gateway software)(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Swasey, Laurence.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft Corp and Micro Decisionware Inc jointly announceDatabase Gateway, a new software link that will let microcomputersrunning DOS or OS/2 applications transparently access data in IBMDB/2 mainframe databases.andP;  Database Gateway connects LAN serversand the mainframe via SQL Server.andP;  Users can obtain data directlythrough any SQL Server front end application.andP;  Microsoft willincorporate Database Gateway in an upcoming release of its Excelspreadsheet, and Borland International Inc will include it in thenext version of its Paradox microcomputer database.andP;  The gatewaywill be available in Jun 1990.andP;  Micro Decisionware will offer adeveloper toolkit to software vendors in Apr 1990.andP;  Users say thenew product solves a long-standing connectivity problem, but someobservers warn that downloading data from a mainframe will be slowand that DB/2 should not be used as a distributed database.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product introduction)Micro Decisionware Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Database Gateway (Communications software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     ConnectivityProduct IntroductionGateways (Interface)Data Base Management SystemsMicro-Mainframe Communication.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>